 Latinos and Asians now constitute a collective majority. Amplifying their voices, Ocampo illustrates how second-generation Filipino Americans' racial identities change depending on the communities they grow up in, the schools they attend, and the people they befriend. Ultimately, The Latinos of Asia offers a window into both the racial consciousness of everyday people and the changing racial landscape of American society.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aFilipino AmericansxRace identityzCaliforniazLos Angeles Region. 0aFilipino AmericansxRace identityzCaliforniazLos Angeles. 0aFilipino AmericanszCaliforniazLos Angeles RegionxEthnic identity. 0aFilipino AmericanszCaliforniazLos Angeles RegionxSocial conditions. 0aFilipino AmericanszCaliforniazLos AngelesxEthnic identity. 0aFilipino AmericanszCaliforniazLos AngelesxSocial conditions. 4aAsian Americans. 4aFilipino Americans. 4aLatinos. 4aassimilation. 4acolonialism. 4aeducation. 4aimmigration. 4aneighborhoods. 4apanethnicity. 4arace and ethnicity. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Discrimination & Race Relations.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311070397940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080479757340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804797573423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804797573.jpg  a978-3-11-070397-9  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles